The '''Bugun liocichla''' ('''''Liocichla bugunorum''''') is a [[passerine]] bird [[species]] from the [[Family (taxonomy)|family]] [[Leiothrichidae]]<ref>{{cite book|author1=Collar, N. J.  |author2=Robson C. |name-list-style=amp |year= 2007|chapter= Family Timaliidae (Babblers)|pages= 70–291|editor=del Hoyo, J.|editor2=Elliott, A.|editor3=Christie, D.A. |title=''[[Handbook of the Birds of the World]]'', Vol. 12. Picathartes to Tits and Chickadees|publisher=Lynx Edicions, Barcelona}}</ref> closely related to the [[Emei Shan liocichla]]. First spotted in 1995 in [[Arunachal Pradesh]], [[India]], it was described as a new species in 2006.<ref name="athreya">
{{cite journal  | last = Athreya  | first = Ramana  | title = A new species of ''Liocichla'' (Aves:Timaliidae) from Eaglenest Wildlife Sanctuary, Arunachal Pradesh, India  | journal = Indian Birds  | volume = 2  | issue = 4  | pages = 82–94  | date = 31 August 2006  | url = http://indianbirds.in/pdfs/IB2.4_Athreya_BugunLiocichla.pdf  | access-date = 31 March 2017  | url-status = live  | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20160304111335/http://indianbirds.in/pdfs/IB2.4_Athreya_BugunLiocichla.pdf  | archive-date = 4 March 2016  }}</ref> The description was made without the collection of a [[Type (zoology)|type specimen]] as they were too few to risk killing one. It is thought to be an endangered species, with a small population, and a very restricted distribution range within which commercial development threatens the habitat.<ref>{{cite book|url=http://www.iiserpune.ac.in/~rathreya/Downloads/athreya2006_ebp.pdf|author=Athreya, R.|year=2006|title=Eaglenest Biodiversity Project − I (2003–2006): Conservation resources for Eaglenest wildlife sanctuary. A report submitted to the Forest Department of the Government of Arunachal Pradesh, India, and the Rufford-Maurice-Laing Foundation (UK)|publisher=Kaati Trust, Pune.|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170331212205/http://www.iiserpune.ac.in/~rathreya/Downloads/athreya2006_ebp.pdf|archive-date=31 March 2017}}</ref>

==Description==
The Bugun liocichla is a small babbler ({{convert|20|cm||abbr=on}}) with olive-grey [[plumage]] and a black cap. The face is marked with prominent orange-yellow lores, and the wings have yellow, red and white patches. The tail is black with crimson coloured undertail coverts and red tips. The feet are pink and the bill is black at the face fading to pale white. A second duller individual was [[mist net]]ted, which was probably the female. The voice is described as fluty and distinctive.<ref name="athreya"/>

A study of the evolution of the species within the genus ''Liocichla'' based on mitochondrial DNA sequence similarity showed that the species is most closely related to ''L. omeiensis'' with the Hengduan Mountains possibly acting as the isolating barrier between the two.<ref>{{cite journal|doi=10.1186/s40657-015-0025-y|title=A multilocus molecular phylogeny for the avian genus ''Liocichla'' (Passeriformes: Leiothrichidae: Liocichla)|journal=Avian Research|volume=6|year=2015|last1=Mays|first1=Herman L|last2=McKay|first2=Bailey D|last3=Tietze|first3=Dieter Thomas|last4=Yao|first4=Cheng-Te|last5=Miller|first5=Lindsey N|last6=Moreland|first6=Kathleen N|last7=Lei|first7=Fumin|article-number=17 |doi-access=free}}{{open access}}</ref>

==Distribution and habitat==
All sightings of the species have been at an altitude of {{convert|2000|m|abbr=on}} on disturbed hillsides covered with shrubs and small trees, with the exception of one sighting on the edge of primary [[forest]]. It lives in a territory similar to that of the [[Emei Shan liocichla]]. Small flocks were observed during January, whereas pairs were observed in May, with an estimated total of 14 individuals.<ref name="athreya"/> It is thought that pairs may hold and defend territories. The Bugun liocichla is only currently known from just one location. Populations may be discovered in other areas of Arunachal Pradesh or neighbouring [[Bhutan]].<ref name="athreya"/>

Attempts have been made to identify new locations where the species could occur based on identification of suitable habitats using computational models.<ref>{{cite journal |author1=Peterson, A. T. |author2=M. Papeş |name-list-style=amp |year=2007 |title=Potential geographic distribution of the Bugun liocichla ''Liocichla bugunorum'', a poorly-known species from north-eastern India |journal=Indian Birds |volume=2 |pages=146–149 |url=http://www.specifysoftware.org/Informatics/bios/biostownpeterson/PP_IB_2006.pdf |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070628044757/http://www.specifysoftware.org/Informatics/bios/biostownpeterson/PP_IB_2006.pdf |archive-date=28 June 2007  }}</ref>

