The species was described in 2006 after being discovered in [[Eaglenest Wildlife Sanctuary]] in [[Arunachal Pradesh]], [[India]], by an [[astrophysicist]], [[Ramana Athreya]].<ref name="Athreya">{{cite web | title = New Multicolored Bird Found in India | agency = Associated Press | date = 12 September 2006 | url = http://apnews.myway.com/article/20060912/D8K3JND00.html | access-date = 14 September 2006 | url-status = live | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20110301220717/http://apnews.myway.com/article/20060912/D8K3JND00.html | archive-date = 1 March 2011}}</ref> The species was first spotted in the sanctuary in 1995 but was not seen again for ten years. Athreya spotted them again in January 2005 but did not publicize it until he was able to confirm it to be a new species. It was initially identified as appearing most similar to an [[Emei Shan liocichla]], ''Liocichla omeiensis'', a species of Liocichla [[endemic (ecology)|endemic]] to [[China]]. It was, however, distinctly different and the full description was finally made by capturing and examining two individuals using mistnets, in May 2006. Due to the apparent rarity of the species no [[Type (zoology)|type specimen]] was collected, instead [[feather]]s from the mist net, photographs, recordings and notes were used as the holotype.<ref name="Athreya"/><ref name="birds">{{cite web | title = Bugun liocichla: a sensational discovery in north-east India | work = Birdlife International | date = 12 September 2006 | url = http://www.birdlife.org/news/news/2006/09/bugun_liocichla.html | access-date = 12 September 2006 | url-status = live | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20061005133918/http://www.birdlife.org/news/news/2006/09/bugun_liocichla.html | archive-date = 5 October 2006}}</ref> The [[International Code of Zoological Nomenclature]] does not allow for new species to be described without the collection of type specimens, but this provision was circumvented in this case by the collection of feathers (the Code allows for "any part of an animal" to be treated as a type specimen; Art. 72.5.1<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.iczn.org/iczn/index.jsp |title=The Code Online &#124; International Commission on Zoological Nomenclature |access-date=31 August 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090524144249/http://www.iczn.org/iczn/index.jsp |archive-date=24 May 2009  }} The International Code of Zoological Nomenclature</ref>). The 1991 description of the [[Bulo Burti boubou]] (''Laniarius liberatus''), an African bushshrike species later considered invalid, lacked a specimen and only blood samples were collected and has been more controversial. A detailed review of the discovery of the species was published in 2007.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Kannan|first=R.|year=2007|title=New bird descriptions without proper voucher specimens: reflections after the Bugun liocichla case|journal=Journal of the Bombay Natural History Society|volume=104|issue=1|pages=12–18}}</ref>

The first report of the species was made in a posting to Nathistory-India, an [[electronic mailing list]] in 1996.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://lists.princeton.edu/cgi-bin/wa?A2=ind9608&L=NATHISTORY-INDIA&P=R1290&I=-3|title=LISTSERV 16.0 – Archives – Error|website=lists.princeton.edu}}</ref> It was only in 2006, however, that the species was formally described.<ref name=desc>{{cite journal |url=http://www.indianbirds.in/images/IB%5B1%5D.2.4.Liocichla.pdf |author=Athreya, R. |year=2006 |title=A new species of ''Liocichla'' (Aves: Timaliidae) from Eaglenest Wildlife Sanctuary, Arunachal Pradesh, India |journal=Indian Birds |volume=2 |issue=4 |pages=82–94 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070316091722/http://www.indianbirds.in/images/IB%5B1%5D.2.4.Liocichla.pdf |archive-date=16 March 2007  }}</ref>

===Taxonomy and systematics===
The species' scientific and common names are derived from the [[Khowa tribe|Bugun tribe]] in whose communal forests the species was discovered.<ref name="birds"/>

The species is a sister of ''Liocichla omeiensis'' and the speciation may have been caused by the isolating geographic barrier of the Hengduan mountains.<ref name=phylo />

==Threats and conservation==
For a "spectacular bird" with distinctive calls to have been overlooked until 1995 suggests that the species is not common. Only three breeding pairs are currently known and it's listed as critically endangered. While the species is capable of living in degraded forests, its small population is considered threatened, especially in the light of plans to build a highway through an area thought to be its primary habitat.<ref name="birds"/>

